Rating: 3
I've made this cake four times in a week-- once in a 10 cup Star of David bundt pan for Hanukkah, and three times in a more traditional 12 cup Nordic Ware bundt pan for Christmas parties. It's an absolutely delicious cake, and I concur with the reviewers who wrote that it improves after a day or two. Make it ahead, let it cool completely, and then wrap well in plastic. I made a simple buttermilk icing for the first one, but I prefer this cake unadorned. I also prefer it with tart granny smith apples and slightly less sugar. My only complaint about this recipe is the cooking time and temperature. At 350 for 90 minutes, it would burn. It takes 80 minutes tops, and I've been lowering the temp by ten degrees toward the end. Watch the cake carefully. It's worth the extra care, because the flavor and texture are both excellent.

Rating: 4
Excellent Cake. I would only add a wonderful glaze the next time. Love the fact it has a firm outside texture and the inside is wonderfully moist. Will definitely make it again.

Rating: 3
This cake is absolutely delicious! Something about it reminds me of Christmas, probably due to the orange zest and cinnamon. I agree with other reviewers that a) you need to loosen the cake with a knife before turning it out (I let it cool completely in the pan, which had been greased and floured) and b) it didn't take 90 minutes to cook. It took more like an hour, so do check it to be safe. The batter will be very thick, so it's more of a "dollop" rather than a "pour" when you put it in the tin. I just spooned it over the apples and spread it a little using the back of the spoon. I will definitely make this one again.

